 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:26"
  "Justin Martyr")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:4"
  "Introductory Note to Irenæus Against Heresies ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:8"
  "Preface.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:10"
  "Chapter I.-Absurd ideas of the
disciples of Valentinus as to the origin, name, order, and conjugal productions
of their fancied Æons, with the passages of Scripture which they adapt to
their opinions.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:12"
  "Chapter II.-The Propator was known to
Monogenes alone. Ambition, disturbance, and danger into which Sophia fell; her
shapeless offspring: she is restored by Horos. The production of Christ and of
the Holy Spirit, in order to the completion of the Æons. Manner of the
production of Jesus.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:14"
  "Chapter III.-Texts of Holy Scripture
used by these heretics to support their opinions.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:16"
  "Chapter IV.-Account given by the
heretics of the formation of Achamoth; origin of the visible world from her
disturbances.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:18"
  "Chapter V.-Formation of the Demiurge;
description of him. He is the creator of everything outside of the Pleroma.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:20"
  "Chapter VI.-The threefold kind of man
feigned by these heretics: good works needless for them, though necessary to
others: their abandoned morals.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:22"
  "Chapter VII.-The mother Achamoth,
when all her seed are perfected, shall pass into the Pleroma, accompanied by
those men who are spiritual; the Demiurge, with animal men, shall pass into the
intermediate habitation; but all material men shall go into corruption. Their
blasphemous opinions against the true incarnation of Christ by the Virgin Mary.
Their views as to the prophecies. Stupid ignorance of the Demiurge.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:24"
  "Chapter VIII.-How the Valentinians
pervert the Scriptures to support their own pious opinions.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:26"
  "Chapter IX.-Refutation of the impious
interpretations of these heretics.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:28"
  "Chapter X.-Unity of the faith of the
Church throughout the whole world.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:30"
  "Chapter XI.-The opinions of
Valentinus, with those of his disciples and others.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:32"
  "Chapter XII.-The doctrines of the
followers of Ptolemy and Colorbasus.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:34"
  "Chapter XIII.-The deceitful arts and
nefarious practices of Marcus.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:36"
  "Chapter XIV.-The various hypotheses
of Marcus and others. Theories respecting letters and syllables.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:38"
  "Chapter XV.-Sige relates to Marcus
the generation of the twenty-four elements and of Jesus. Exposure of these
absurdities.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:40"
  "Chapter XVI.-Absurd interpretations
of the Marcosians.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:42"
  "Chapter XVII.-The theory of the
Marcosians, that created things were made after the image of things invisible.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:44"
  "Chapter XVIII.-Passages from Moses,
which the heretics pervert to the support of their hypothesis.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:46"
  "Chapter XIX.-Passages of Scripture by
which they attempt to prove that the Supreme Father was unknown before the
coming of Christ.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:48"
  "Chapter XX.-The apocryphal and
spurious Scriptures of the Marcosians, with passages of the Gospels which they
pervert.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:50"
  "Chapter XXI.-The views of redemption
entertained by these heretics.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:52"
  "Chapter XXII.-Deviations of heretics
from the truth.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:54"
  "Chapter XXIII.-Doctrines and
practices of Simon Magus and Menander.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:56"
  "Chapter XXIV.-Doctrines of Saturninus
and Basilides.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:58"
  "Chapter XXV.-Doctrines of
Carpocrates.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:60"
  "Chapter XXVI.-Doctrines of Cerinthus,
the Ebionites, and Nicolaitanes.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:62"
  "Chapter XXVII.-Doctrines of Cerdo and
Marcion.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:64"
  "Chapter XXVIII.-Doctrines of Tatian,
the Encratites, and others.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:66"
  "Chapter XXIX.-Doctrines of various
other Gnostic sects, and especially of the Barbeliotes or Borborians.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:68"
  "Chapter XXX.-Doctrines of the Ophites
and Sethians.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8:70"
  "Chapter XXXI.-Doctrines of the
Cainites.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:8"
  "Against Heresies: Book I ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:8"
  "Preface.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:10"
  "Chapter I.-There is but one God: the
impossibility of its being otherwise.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:12"
  "Chapter II.-The world was not formed
by angels, or by any other being, contrary to the will of the most high God,
but was made by the Father through the Word. [This noble chapter is a sort of homily on
Heb. i.]
")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:14"
  "Chapter III.-The Bythus and Pleroma
of the Valentinians, as well as the God of Marcion, shown to be absurd; the
world was actually created by the same Being who had conceived the idea of it,
and was not the fruit of defect or ignorance.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:16"
  "Chapter IV.-The absurdity of the
supposed vacuum and defect of the heretics is demonstrated.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:18"
  "Chapter V.-This world was not formed
by any other beings within the territory which is contained by the Father.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:20"
  "Chapter VI.-The angels and the
Creator of the world could not have been ignorant of the Supreme God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:22"
  "Chapter VII.-Created things are not
the images of those Æons who are within the Pleroma.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:24"
  "Chapter VIII.-Created things are not
a shadow of the Pleroma.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:26"
  "Chapter IX.-There is but one Creator
of the world, God the Father: this the constant belief of the Church.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:28"
  "Chapter X.-Perverse interpretations
of Scripture by the heretics: God created all things out of nothing, and not
from pre-existent matter.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:30"
  "Chapter XI.-The heretics, from their
disbelief of the truth, have fallen into an abyss of error: reasons for
investigating their systems.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:32"
  "Chapter XII.-The Triacontad of the
heretics errs both by defect and excess: Sophia could never have produced
anything apart from her consort; Logos and Sige could not have been
contemporaries.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:34"
  "Chapter XIII.-The first order of
production maintained by the heretics is altogether indefensible.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:36"
  "Chapter XIV.-Valentinus and his
followers derived the principles of their system from the heathen; the names
only are changed.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:38"
  "Chapter XV.-No account can be given
of these productions.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:40"
  "Chapter XVI.-The Creator of the world
either produced of Himself the images of things to be made, or the Pleroma was
formed after the image of some previous system; and so on ad infinitum.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:42"
  "Chapter XVII.-Inquiry into the
production of the Æons: whatever its supposed nature, it is in every respect
inconsistent; and on the hypothesis of the heretics, even Nous and the Father
Himself would be stained with ignorance.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:44"
  "Chapter XVIII.-Sophia was never
really in ignorance or passion; her Enthymesis could not have been separated
from herself, or exhibited special tendencies of its own.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:46"
  "Chapter XIX.-Absurdities of the
heretics as to their own origin: their opinions respecting the Demiurge shown
to be equally untenable and ridiculous.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:48"
  "Chapter XX.-Futility of the arguments
adduced to demonstrate the sufferings of the twelfth Æon, from the parables,
the treachery of Judas, and the passion of our Saviour.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:50"
  "Chapter XXI.-The twelve apostles were
not a type of the Æons.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:52"
  "Chapter XXII.-The thirty Æons are
not typified by the fact that Christ was baptized in His thirtieth year: He did
not suffer in the twelfth month after His baptism, but was more than fifty
years old when He died.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:54"
  "Chapter XXIII.-The woman who suffered
from an issue of blood was no type of the suffering Æon.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:56"
  "Chapter XXIV.-Folly of the arguments
derived by the heretics from numbers, letters, and syllables.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:58"
  "Chapter XXV.-God is not to be sought
after by means of letters, syllables, and numbers; necessity of humility in
such investigations.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:60"
  "Chapter XXVI.-\"Knowledge puffeth up,
but love edifieth.\"")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:62"
  "Chapter XXVII.-Proper mode of
interpreting parables and obscure passages of Scripture.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:64"
  "Chapter XXVIII.-Perfect knowledge
cannot be attained in the present life: many questions must be submissively
left in the hands of God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:66"
  "Chapter XXIX.-Refutation of the views
of the heretics as to the future destiny of the soul and body.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:68"
  "Chapter XXX.-Absurdity of their
styling themselves spiritual, while the Demiurge is declared to be animal.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:70"
  "Chapter XXXI.-Recapitulation and
application of the foregoing arguments.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:72"
  "Chapter XXXII.-Further exposure of
the wicked and blasphemous doctrines of the heretics.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:74"
  "Chapter XXXIII.-Absurdity of the
doctrine of the transmigration of souls.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:76"
  "Chapter XXXIV.-Souls can be
recognised in the separate state, and are immortal although they once had a
beginning.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12:78"
  "Chapter XXXV.-Refutation of
Basilides, and of the opinion that the prophets uttered their predictions under
the inspiration of different gods.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:12"
  "Against Heresies: Book II ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:8"
  "Preface.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:10"
  "Chapter I.-The apostles did not
commence to preach the Gospel, or to place anything on record until they were
endowed with the gifts and power of the Holy Spirit. They preached one God
alone, Maker of heaven and earth.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:12"
  "Chapter II.-The heretics follow
neither Scripture nor tradition.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:14"
  "Chapter III.-A refutation of the
heretics, from the fact that, in the various Churches, a perpetual succession
of bishops was kept up.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:16"
  "Chapter IV.-The truth is to be found
nowhere else but in the Catholic Church, the sole depository of apostolical
doctrine. Heresies are of recent formation, and cannot trace their origin up to
the apostles.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:18"
  "Chapter V.-Christ and His apostles,
without any fraud, deception, or hypocrisy, preached that one God, the Father,
was the founder of all things. They did not accommodate their doctrine to the
prepossessions of their hearers.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:20"
  "Chapter VI-The Holy Ghost, throughout
the Old Testament Scriptures, made mention of no other God or Lord, save him
who is the true God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:22"
  "Chapter VII.-Reply to an objection
founded on the words of St. Paul (2 Cor. iv. 4). St. Paul occasionally uses words not in their
grammatical sequence.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:24"
  "Chapter VIII.-Answer to an objection,
arising from the words of Christ (Matt. vi. 24). God alone is to be really called God and Lord,
for He is without beginning and end.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:26"
  "Chapter IX.-One and the same God, the
Creator of heaven and earth, is He whom the prophets foretold, and who was
declared by the Gospel. Proof of this, at the outset, from St. Matthew's
Gospel.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:28"
  "Chapter X.-Proofs of the foregoing,
drawn from the Gospels of Mark and Luke.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:30"
  "Chapter XI-Proofs in continuation,
extracted from St. John's Gospel. The Gospels are four in number, neither more
nor less. Mystic reasons for this.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:32"
  "Chapter XII.-Doctrine of the rest of
the apostles.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:34"
  "Chapter XIII-Refutation of the
opinion, that Paul was the only apostle who had knowledge of the truth.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:36"
  "Chapter XIV.-If Paul had known any
mysteries unrevealed to the other apostles, Luke, his constant companion and
fellow-traveller, could not have been ignorant of them; neither could the truth
have possibly lain hid from him, through whom alone we learn many and most
important particulars of the Gospel history.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:38"
  "Chapter XV.-Refutation of the
Ebionites, who disparaged the authority of St. Paul, from the writings of St.
Luke, which must be received as a whole. Exposure of the hypocrisy, deceit, and
pride of the Gnostics. The apostles and their disciples knew and preached one
God, the Creator of the world.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:40"
  "Chapter XVI.-Proofs from the
apostolic writings, that Jesus Christ was one and the same, the only begotten
Son of God, perfect God and perfect man.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:42"
  "Chapter XVII.-The apostles teach that
it was neither Christ nor the Saviour, but the Holy Spirit, who did descend
upon Jesus. The reason for this descent.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:44"
  "Chapter XVIII.-Continuation of the
foregoing argument. Proofs from the writings of St. Paul, and from the words of
Our Lord, that Christ and Jesus cannot be considered as distinct beings;
neither can it be alleged that the Son of God became man merely in appearance,
but that He did so truly and actually.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:46"
  "Chapter XIX.-Jesus Christ was not a
mere man, begotten from Joseph in the ordinary course of nature, but was very
God, begotten of the Father most high, and very man, born of the Virgin.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:48"
  "Chapter XX.-God showed himself, by
the fall of man, as patient, benign, merciful, mighty to save. Man is therefore
most ungrateful, if, unmindful of his own lot, and of the benefits held out to
him, he do not acknowledge divine grace.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:50"
  "Chapter XXI.-A vindication of the
prophecy in Isa. vii. 14 against the misinterpretations of Theodotion,
Aquila, the Ebionites, and the Jews. Authority of the Septuagint version.
Arguments in proof that Christ was born of a virgin.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:52"
  "Chapter XXII.-Christ assumed actual
flesh, conceived and born of the Virgin.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:54"
  "Chapter XXIII.-Arguments in
opposition to Tatian, showing that it was consonant to divine justice and mercy
that the first Adam should first partake in that salvation offered to all by
Christ.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:56"
  "Chapter XXIV.-Recapitulation of the
various arguments adduced against Gnostic impiety under all its aspects. The
heretics, tossed about by every blast of doctrine, are opposed by the uniform
teaching of the Church, which remains so always, and is consistent with itself.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16:58"
  "Chapter XXV.-This world is ruled by
the providence of one God, who is both endowed with infinite justice to punish
the wicked, and with infinite goodness to bless the pious, and impart to them
salvation. ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:16"
  "Against Heresies: Book III ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:18"
  "Elucidation")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:8"
  "Preface.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:10"
  "Chapter I.-The Lord acknowledged but
one God and Father.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:12"
  "Chapter II.-Proofs from the plain
testimony of Moses, and of the other prophets, whose words are the words of
Christ, that there is but one God, the founder of the world, whom Our Lord
preached, and whom He called His Father.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:14"
  "Chapter III.-Answer to the cavils of
the Gnostics. We are not to suppose that the true God can be changed, or come
to an end because the heavens, which are His throne and the earth, His
footstool, shall pass away.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:16"
  "Chapter IV.-Answer to another
objection, showing that the destruction of Jerusalem, which was the city of the
great King, diminished nothing from the supreme majesty and power of God, for
that this destruction was put in execution by the most wise counsel of the same
God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:18"
  "Chapter V.-The author returns to his
former argument, and shows that there was but one God announced by the law and
prophets, whom Christ confesses as His Father, and who, through His word, one
living God with Him, made Himself known to men in both covenants.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:20"
  "Chapter VI.-Explanation of the words
of Christ, \"No man knoweth the Father, but the Son,\" etc.; which words the
heretics misinterpret. Proof that, by the Father revealing the Son, and by the
Son being revealed, the Father was never unknown.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:22"
  "Chapter VII.-Recapitulation of the
foregoing argument, showing that Abraham, through the revelation of the Word,
knew the Father, and the coming of the Son of God. For this cause, he rejoiced
to see the day of Christ, when the promises made to him should be fulfilled.
The fruit of this rejoicing has flowed to posterity, viz., to those who are
partakers in the faith of Abraham, but not to the Jews who reject the Word of
God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:24"
  "Chapter VIII.-Vain attempts of
Marcion and his followers, who exclude Abraham from the salvation bestowed by
Christ, who liberated not only Abraham, but the seed of Abraham, by fulfilling
and not destroying the law when He healed on the Sabbath-day.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:26"
  "Chapter IX.-There is but one author,
and one end to both covenants.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:28"
  "Chapter X.-The Old Testament
Scriptures, and those written by Moses in particular, do everywhere make
mention of the Son of God, and foretell His advent and passion. From this fact
it follows that they were inspired by one and the same God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:30"
  "Chapter XI.-The old prophets and
righteous men knew beforehand of the advent of Christ, and earnestly desired to
see and hear Him, He revealing himself in the Scriptures by the Holy Ghost, and
without any change in Himself, enriching men day by day with benefits, but
conferring them in greater abundance on later than on former generations.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:32"
  "Chapter XII.-It clearly appears that
there was but one author of both the old and the new law, from the fact that
Christ condemned traditions and customs repugnant to the former, while He
confirmed its most important precepts, and taught that He was Himself the end
of the Mosaic law.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:34"
  "Chapter XIII.-Christ did not abrogate
the natural precepts of the law, but rather fulfilled and extended them. He
removed the yoke and bondage of the old law, so that mankind, being now set
free, might serve God with that trustful piety which becometh sons.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:36"
  "Chapter XIV.-If God demands obedience
from man, if He formed man, called him and placed him under laws, it was merely
for man's welfare; not that God stood in need of man, but that He graciously
conferred upon man His favours in every possible manner.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:38"
  "Chapter XV.-At first God deemed it
sufficient to inscribe the natural law, or the Decalogue, upon the hearts of
men; but afterwards He found it necessary to bridle, with the yoke of the
Mosaic law, the desires of the Jews, who were abusing their liberty; and even
to add some special commands, because of the hardness of their hearts.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:40"
  "Chapter XVI.-Perfect righteousness
was conferred neither by circumcision nor by any other legal ceremonies. The
Decalogue, however, was not cancelled by Christ, but is always in force: men
were never released from its commandments.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:42"
  "Chapter XVII.-Proof that God did not
appoint the Levitical dispensation for His own sake, or as requiring such
service; for He does, in fact, need nothing from men.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:44"
  "Chapter XVIII.-Concerning sacrifices
and oblations, and those who truly offer them.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:46"
  "Chapter XIX.-Earthly things may be
the type of heavenly, but the latter cannot be the types of others still
superior and unknown; nor can we, without absolute madness, maintain that God
is known to us only as the type of a still unknown and superior being.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:48"
  "Chapter XX.-That one God formed all
things in the world, by means of the Word and the Holy Spirit: and that
although He is to us in this life invisible and incomprehensible, nevertheless
He is not unknown; inasmuch as His works do declare Him, and His Word has shown
that in many modes He may be seen and known.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:50"
  "Chapter XXI.-Abraham's faith was
identical with ours; this faith was prefigured by the words and actions of the
old patriarchs.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:52"
  "Chapter XXII.-Christ did not come for
the sake of the men of one age only, but for all who, living righteously and
piously, had believed upon Him; and for those, too, who shall believe.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:54"
  "Chapter XXIII.-The patriarchs and
prophets by pointing out the advent of Christ, fortified thereby, as it were,
the way of posterity to the faith of Christ; and so the labours of the apostles
were lessened inasmuch as they gathered in the fruits of the labours of others.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:56"
  "Chapter XXIV.-The conversion of the
Gentiles was more difficult than that of the Jews; the labours of those
apostles, therefore who engaged in the former task, were greater than those who
undertook the latter.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:58"
  "Chapter XXV.-Both covenants were
prefigured in Abraham, and in the labour of Tamar; there was, however, but one
and the same God to each covenant.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:60"
  "Chapter XXVI.-The treasure hid in the
Scriptures is Christ; the true exposition of the Scriptures is to be found in
the Church alone.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:62"
  "Chapter XXVII-The sins of the men of
old time, which incurred the displeasure of God, were, by His providence,
committed to writing, that we might derive instruction thereby, and not be
filled with pride. We must not, therefore, infer that there was another God
than He whom Christ preached; we should rather fear, lest the one and the same
God who inflicted punishment on the ancients, should bring down heavier upon
us.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:64"
  "Chapter XXVIII.-Those persons prove
themselves senseless who exaggerate the mercy of Christ, but are silent as to
the judgment, and look only at the more abundant grace of the New Testament;
but, forgetful of the greater degree of perfection which it demands from us,
they endeavour to show that there is another God beyond Him who created the
world.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:66"
  "Chapter XXIX.-Refutation of the
arguments of the Marcionites, who attempted to show that God was the author of
sin, because He blinded Pharaoh and his servants.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:68"
  "Chapter XXX.-Refutation of another
argument adduced by the Marcionites, that God directed the Hebrews to spoil the
Egyptians.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:70"
  "Chapter XXXI.-We should not hastily
impute as crimes to the men of old time those actions which the Scripture has
not condemned, but should rather seek in them types of things to come: an
example of this in the incest committed by Lot.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:72"
  "Chapter XXXII.-That one God was the
author of both Testaments, is confirmed by the authority of a presbyter who had
been taught by the apostles.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:74"
  "Chapter XXXIII.-Whosoever confesses
that one God is the author of both Testaments, and diligently reads the Scriptures
in company with the presbyters of the Church, is a true spiritual disciple; and
he will rightly understand and interpret all that the prophets have declared
respecting Christ and the liberty of the New Testament.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:76"
  "Chapter XXXIV.-Proof against the
Marcionites, that the prophets referred in all their predictions to our Christ.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:78"
  "Chapter XXXV.-A refutation of those
who allege that the prophets uttered some predictions under the inspiration of
the highest, others from the Demiurge. Disagreements of the Valentinians among
themselves with regard to these same predictions.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:80"
  "Chapter XXXVI.-The prophets were sent
from one and the same Father from whom the Son was sent.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:82"
  "Chapter XXXVII.-Men are possessed of
free will, and endowed with the faculty of making a choice. It is not true,
therefore, that some are by nature good, and others bad.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:84"
  "Chapter XXXVIII.-Why man was not made
perfect from the beginning. ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:86"
  "Chapter XXXIX.-Man is endowed with
the faculty of distinguishing good and evil; so that, without compulsion, he
has the power, by his own will and choice, to perform God's commandments, by
doing which he avoids the evils prepared for the rebellious.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:88"
  "Chapter XL.-One and the same God the
Father inflicts punishment on the reprobate, and bestows rewards on the elect.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22:90"
  "Chapter XLI.-Those persons who do not
believe in God, but who are disobedient, are angels and sons of the devil, not
indeed by nature, but by imitation. Close of this book, and scope of the
succeeding one.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:22"
  "Against Heresies: Book IV ")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:8"
  "Preface.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:10"
  "Chapter I.-Christ alone is able to
teach divine things, and to redeem us: He, the same, took flesh of the Virgin
Mary, not merely in appearance, but actually, by the operation of the Holy
Spirit, in order to renovate us. Strictures on the conceits of Valentinus and
Ebion.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:12"
  "Chapter II.-When Christ visited us in
His grace, He did not come to what did not belong to Him: also, by shedding His
true blood for us, and exhibiting to us His true flesh in the Eucharist, He
conferred upon our flesh the capacity of salvation.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:14"
  "Chapter III.-The power and glory of
God shine forth in the weakness of human flesh, as He will render our body a
participator of the resurrection and of immortality, although He has formed it
from the dust of the earth; He will also bestow upon it the enjoyment of
immortality, just as He grants it this short life in common with the soul.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:16"
  "Chapter IV.-Those persons are
deceived who feign another God the Father besides the Creator of the world; for
he must have been feeble and useless, or else malignant and full of envy, if he
be either unable or unwilling to extend external life to our bodies.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:18"
  "Chapter V.-The prolonged life of the
ancients, the translation of Elijah and of Enoch in their own bodies, as well
as the preservation of Jonah, of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, in the midst
of extreme peril, are clear demonstrations that God can raise up our bodies to
life eternal.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:20"
  "Chapter VI.-God will bestow salvation
upon the whole nature of man, consisting of body and soul in close union, since
the Word took it upon Him, and adorned with the gifts of the Holy Spirit, of
whom our bodies are, and are termed, the temples.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:22"
  "Chapter VII.-Inasmuch as Christ did
rise in our flesh, it follows that we shall be also raised in the same; since the
resurrection promised to us should not be referred to spirits naturally
immortal, but to bodies in themselves mortal.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:24"
  "Chapter VIII.-The gifts of the Holy
Spirit which we receive prepare us for incorruption, render us spiritual, and
separate us from carnal men. These two classes are signified by the clean and
unclean animals in the legal dispensation.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:26"
  "Chapter IX.-Showing how that passage
of the apostle which the heretics pervert, should be understood; viz., \"Flesh
and blood shall not possess the kingdom of God.\"")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:28"
  "Chapter X.-By a comparison drawn from
the wild olive-tree, whose quality but not whose nature is changed by grafting,
he proves more important things; he points out also that man without the Spirit
is not capable of bringing forth fruit, or of inheriting the kingdom of God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:30"
  "Chapter XI.-Treats upon the actions
of carnal and of spiritual persons; also, that the spiritual cleansing is not
to be referred to the substance of our bodies, but to the manner of our former
life.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:32"
  "Chapter XII.-Of the difference
between life and death; of the breath of life and the vivifying Spirit: also
how it is that the substance of flesh revives which once was dead.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:34"
  "Chapter XIII.-In the dead who were
raised by Christ we possess the highest proof of the resurrection; and our
hearts are shown to be capable of life eternal, because they can now receive
the Spirit of God.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:36"
  "Chapter XIV.-Unless the flesh were to
be saved, the Word would not have taken upon Him flesh of the same substance as
ours: from this it would follow that neither should we have been reconciled by
Him.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:38"
  "Chapter XV.-Proofs of the
resurrection from Isaiah and Ezekiel; the same God who created us will also
raise us up.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:40"
  "Chapter XVI.-Since our bodies return
to the earth, it follows that they have their substance from it; also, by the
advent of the Word, the image of God in us appeared in a clearer light.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:42"
  "Chapter XVII.-There is but one Lord
and one God, the Father and Creator of all things, who has loved us in Christ,
given us commandments, and remitted our sins; whose Son and Word Christ proved
Himself to be, when He forgave our sins.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:44"
  "Chapter XVIII.-God the Father and His
Word have formed all created things (which They use) by Their own power and
wisdom, not out of defect or ignorance. The Son of God, who received all power
from the Father, would otherwise never have taken flesh upon Him.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:46"
  "Chapter XIX.-A comparison is
instituted between the disobedient and sinning Eve and the Virgin Mary, her
patroness. Various and discordant heresies are mentioned.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:48"
  "Chapter XX.-Those pastors are to be
heard to whom the apostles committed the Churches, possessing one and the same
doctrine of salvation; the heretics, on the other hand, are to be avoided. We
must think soberly with regard to the mysteries of the faith.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:50"
  "Chapter XXI.-Christ is the head of
all things already mentioned. It was fitting that He should be sent by the
Father, the Creator of all things, to assume human nature, and should be
tempted by Satan, that He might fulfil the promises, and carry off a glorious
and perfect victory.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:52"
  "Chapter XXII.-The true Lord and the
one God is declared by the law, and manifested by Christ His Son in the Gospel;
whom alone we should adore, and from Him we must look for all good things, not
from Satan.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:54"
  "Chapter XXIII.-The devil is well
practised in falsehood, by which Adam having been led astray, sinned on the
sixth day of the creation, in which day also he has been renewed by Christ.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:56"
  "Chapter XXIV.-Of the constant
falsehood of the devil, and of the powers and governments of the world, which
we ought to obey, inasmuch as they are appointed of God, not of the devil.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:58"
  "Chapter XXV.-The fraud, pride, and
tyrannical kingdom of Antichrist, as described by Daniel and Paul.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:60"
  "Chapter XXVI.-John and Daniel have
predicted the dissolution and desolation of the Roman Empire, which shall
precede the end of the world and the eternal kingdom of Christ. The Gnostics are
refuted, those tools of Satan, who invent another Father different from the
Creator.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:62"
  "Chapter XXVII.-The future judgment by
Christ. Communion with and separation from the divine being. The eternal
punishment of unbelievers.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:64"
  "Chapter XXVIII.-The distinction to be
made between the righteous and the wicked. The future apostasy in the time of
Antichrist, and the end of the world.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:66"
  "Chapter XXIX.-All things have been
created for the service of man. The deceits, wickedness, and apostate power of
Antichrist. This was prefigured at the deluge, as afterwards by the persecution
of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:68"
  "Chapter XXX.-Although certain as to
the number of the name of Antichrist, yet we should come to no rash conclusions
as to the name itself, because this number is capable of being fitted to many
names. Reasons for this point being reserved by the Holy Spirit. Antichrist's
reign and death.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:70"
  "Chapter XXXI.-The preservation of our
bodies is confirmed by the resurrection and ascension of Christ: the souls of
the saints during the intermediate period are in a state of expectation of that
time when they shall receive their perfect and consummated glory.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:72"
  "Chapter XXXII.-In that flesh in which
the saints have suffered so many afflictions, they shall receive the fruits of
their labours; especially since all creation waits for this, and God promises
it to Abraham and his seed.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:74"
  "Chapter XXXIII.-Further proofs of the
same proposition, drawn from the promises made by Christ, when He declared that
He would drink of the fruit of the vine with His disciples in His Father's
kingdom, while at the same time He promised to reward them an hundred-fold, and
to make them partake of banquets. The blessing pronounced by Jacob had pointed
out this already, as Papias and the elders have interpreted it.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:76"
  "Chapter XXXIV.-He fortifies his
opinions with regard to the temporal and earthly kingdom of the saints after
their resurrection, by the various testimonies of Isaiah, Ezekiel, Jeremiah,
and Daniel; also by the parable of the servants watching, to whom the Lord
promised that He would minister.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:78"
  "Chapter XXXV.-He contends that these
testimonies already alleged cannot be understood allegorically of celestial
blessings, but that they shall have their fulfilment after the coming of
Antichrist, and the resurrection, in the terrestrial Jerusalem. To the former
prophecies he subjoins others drawn from Isaiah, Jeremiah, and the Apocalypse
of John.")
 (#P"/var/www/got/public/charito-wt/compiled-resources/anf01:28:26:80"
  "Chapter XXXVI.-Men shall be actually
raised: the world shall not be annihilated; but there shall be various mansions
for the saints, according to the rank allotted to each individual. All things
shall be subject to God the Father, and so shall He be all in all.")
